Running the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.15.169 -p 22,3306,9999,15065,16109,46969 against the six open TCP ports returns the result above. By the looks of it, there is a HTTP server running on port 15065, some unknown application on port 16109, and a telnet on port 46969 as shown above. I will start enumeration with the higher port applications first.

Enumeration

Port 15065: HTTP

Browsing to this port via a web browser displays the webpage above. Apparently the website is down for maintenance, however the username dan is interesting as it could be a valid & useful username in later stage. Viewing the source-code of this webpage does not contain anything useful either. Time to perform a directory search to identify any hidden directories.


Using the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.15.169:15065/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x html,php,txt, I identified an interesting directory called monitor as shown above. Is this a web application we can use?


The web application is displayed above for the monitor directory. It seems to be a ping checker. I entered the IP address 127.0.0.1 and pressed Ping and got a hit. Is this web application vulnerable to command injection by any chance? Before performing an attacks, I wish to enumerate further.


Reading through the source-code of the webpage contains some crucial information, as shown above. The JavaScript of the web application is viewable. And there are some disclosed comments left behind by the developers which are interesting. When the Ping button is pressed, the JavaScript function pingHost() seems to be executed. Maybe it is possible to read this function to identify any weaknesses?


The JavaScript source code is obfuscated, as shown above. There is another username called steve which is interesting and useful.


Using an online JavaScript deobfuscator to deobfuscate the source code, I obtained the result above. The function pingHost() seems to be sending data to /api/cmd. And it is using ping -c 4 <IP> to perform the ping. The ValidateIPaddress() function also contains the code to validate the entered IP addresses via regex.

Port 3306: MySQL

I notice there is MySQL port open on the target machine. Using the command mysql -h 10.10.15.169 -u root -p and the password root, I gained access to the MySQL database. Running the command show databases; shows there is an unusual database called users.


After enumerating the database for some time, I identified the table called User. This table contains the credentials ramen:noodlesRTheBest and some flag, as shown above. Maybe I can use this credentials to gain access via SSH?

Exploitation


Using the credentials ramen:noodlesRTheBest, I am able to SSH into the target machine as the user ramen as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as the user ramen.

Privilege Escalation & Flags


Running the command ls -la shows there are multiple users on the target machine, as shown above.


There is one more flag located inside the home directory of user bread, as shown above.


Another flag is located inside the home directory of user food, as shown above.


There is an interesting user called tryhackme with two interesting files as shown above. Maybe these files are hiding information?


Using the command python3 -m http.server 8008, I started a Python HTTP server on the target machine at port 8008. Then on my machine, I am able to access the files directly via a web browser as shown above. I transferred the binary executable img to my machine but I did not find anything useful.


After some enumeration, I decided to perform privilege escalation to root. Running the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null returns two interesting entries with SUID bit set: /usr/bin/vim.basic and /usr/bin/screen-4.5.0 as shown above. Is the target machine vulnerable to the GNU Screen 4.5.0 - Local Privilege Escalation? Also, can vim.basic be used to open a root shell?


Running the command /usr/bin/vim.basic -c ':py3 import os; os.execl("/bin/sh", "sh", "-pc", "reset; exec sh -p")' opens a root shell, as shown above. The root flag is shown above too.
